<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What internal temperature is safe for chicken?", answer: "Chicken and all poultry must reach an internal temperature of 165 degrees F (74 degrees C) in the thickest part. This applies to whole birds, breasts, thighs, wings, and ground poultry. Use an instant-read thermometer for accuracy." },
  { question: "How long per pound for a beef roast?", answer: "At 325-350 degrees F, a beef roast takes approximately 15 minutes per pound for rare (125 F internal), 18 minutes for medium-rare (135 F), 20 minutes for medium (145 F), and 27 minutes for well-done (165 F)." },
  { question: "Should I rest meat after cooking?", answer: "Yes. Resting allows juices to redistribute throughout the meat. Small cuts like steaks need 5-10 minutes. Large roasts need 15-20 minutes. Brisket and pulled pork benefit from 30-60 minutes of rest." },
  { question: "How do I know when meat is done without a thermometer?", answer: "While a thermometer is the most reliable method, you can use the touch test for steaks (comparing firmness to parts of your palm), check that poultry juices run clear, or cut into the thickest part. However, a digital instant-read thermometer is strongly recommended for food safety." },
  { question: "Does bone-in meat take longer to cook?", answer: "Bone-in cuts may take slightly longer because bone conducts heat slower than meat. However, bones also help distribute heat evenly. A good rule is to add 5-10 minutes of total cooking time for bone-in versus boneless cuts of similar weight." }
]) %>

